Certainly! Below is a simple Java program that reverses the characters of a given string:

```java
public class StringReverser {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example string to reverse
        String inputString = "Hello, World!";

        // Call the reverseString method
        String reversedString = reverseString(inputString);

        // Output the result
        System.out.println("Original String: " + inputString);
        System.out.println("Reversed String: " + reversedString);
    }

    // Method to reverse a string
    public static String reverseString(String str) {
        // Convert the string to a character array
        char[] charArray = str.toCharArray();

        // Initialize pointers for the start and end of the array
        int left = 0;
        int right = charArray.length - 1;

        // Swap characters while traversing the array from both ends
        while (left < right) {
            // Swap the characters at left and right positions
            char temp = charArray[left];
            charArray[left] = charArray[right];
            charArray[right] = temp;

            // Move the pointers towards the center
            left++;
            right--;
        }

        // Convert the character array back to a string and return
        return new String(charArray);
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
- The program defines a method `reverseString` that takes a string as input and returns its reversed version.
- It converts the string into a character array to facilitate swapping of characters.
- Two pointers (`left` and `right`) are used to traverse the character array from both ends. Characters are swapped until the pointers meet in the middle.
- The reversed character array is then converted back into a string and returned.

You can test this program with different input strings to see how it handles them.
